{"title":"Week 1 Introduction to Remote Sensing","markdown":{"headingText":"Week 1 Introduction to Remote Sensing","headingAttr":{"id":"","classes":["unnumbered"],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n## Overview\n\nFor the first week, we are introduced to the concept of remote sensing and how to download data and images collected by satellites and perform basic analysis with SNAP and R.\n\nRemote sensing is part of GIS but it involves more than just GIS.\n\n## Remote Sensing Overview\n\n-   Active vs Passive sensors\n    -   Active\n    -   Passive\n-   Data in Remote Sensing: Mainly raster data.\n-   Four resolutions: Remotely sensed data and applications will vary based on the four resolutions\n    -   Spatial = the size of the raster grid per pixel (e.g. 20cm or 30m)\n    -   Spectral = the number of bands it records data in... more soon\n    -   Temporal = the time it revisits (e.g. daily, every 7 days, on demand ✈️)\n    -   Radiometric = identify differences in light or reflectance, in practice this is the range of possible values.\n-   \n    -   an 8-bit sensor has values between 0 and 255 (256 possibilities)\n    -   an 11-bit sensor has values between 0 and 2047(2048 possibilities)\n\n## Case Study of Bristol\n\nFor this practical, I picked Bristol as its distinct urban and suburb area split. The data is downloaded from [EU Copernicus Data Portal](https://dataspace.copernicus.eu/) and [Earth Explorer](https://earthexplorer.usgs.gov). The Sentinel 2A data is from April 17th, 2022 and the Landsat 8 data is from Sept 07th, 2023.\n\nFirst, I performed a scatter analysis for the greater Bristol area that I have picked for the analysis, this includes a large portion of suburb land, which indicates high biomass in the analysis.\n\n![Scatter Plot Analysis](images/scatterplot.png){fig-align=\"center\" width=\"792\"}\n\n![Histogram Analysis](images/histogram.png){fig-align=\"center\" width=\"736\"}\n\n![Sentinel 2 Image](images/sent2.png){fig-align=\"center\" width=\"735\"}\n\n![Sentinel and Landsat Side-by-side](images/Screenshot%202024-01-29%20190738.png){fig-align=\"center\" width=\"734\"}\n\nLater on, I performed the down sampling for Sentinel-2A images to align its resolution with Landsat images.\n\n![Down-sampling of Sentinel-2A Images](images/resampling.png){fig-align=\"center\" width=\"495\"}\n\n## Results\n\nAfter down-sampling Sentinel images and cross-analyzing it with LandSat of the POI, downtown area of Bristol, the result is recorded below, indicating high urban.\n\n![Week 1 Result](images/Screenshot%202024-01-29%20202650.png){fig-align=\"center\" width=\"647\"}\n\n## Reflections\n\nRemote sensing is certainly more than what I have previously pictured, which involves mainly a great deal of image processing. On the contrary, it consists of a balanced amount of geophysics, actual physics, and last but not least geography. [@navalgund2007remote] In short, it is an interdisciplinary realm comprised of decades of studies and applications. While traditional image processing or computer vision certainly plays an important role, [@wilkinson1999recent] further development in remote sensing certainly will demand a deep understanding of GIS, atmospheric science, spectral analysis, environmental science, ecology, and sensor technology etc.\n\nAside from the metaphysical overview of remote sensing as an interesting area of research, I further browsed around [EU Copernicus Data Portal](https://dataspace.copernicus.eu/) and [Earth Explorer](https://earthexplorer.usgs.gov) to see what data I can have access for future research uses within and beyond the module.\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":false,"echo":true,"output":true,"warning":true,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":